Department of Justice Top 10 Leading Contractor Analysis (FY23-24)

Overview

This notebook presents an analysis of USASpending data, conducted by Tony McGovern It provides valuable insights for DOJ leadership to optimize procurement practices, reduce unnecessary contractor dependency, provide stability to the federal workforce, and ensure maximum value for taxpayer resources. It examines the contracting patterns between the Department of Justice (DOJ) and the top 10 U.S. federal government contractors across fiscal years 2023-2024. The study provides insights into spending patterns, competitive dynamics, and performance metrics for major government contractors.

Findings

This analysis reveals uneven distribution of contract obligations, varying engagement models, and distinct quarterly spending patterns. Specialized relationships exist between contractors and DOJ components, with varying levels of competition and contract durations. Modification patterns highlight differences in contractors' ability to expand contract scope.

Contract Volume and Value

  • Total DOJ contract obligations are distributed unevenly across contractors, with significant concentration among the top 10 U.S. federal government performers
  • Average contract sizes vary substantially between contractors, indicating different engagement models
  • The analysis reveals which contractors capture the largest percentage of DOJ's overall contract spending

Temporal Patterns

  • Contract awards show distinct quarterly patterns throughout the fiscal years
  • Year-over-year growth rates between FY23 and FY24 highlight evolving contractor relationships
  • Several contractors demonstrate consistent quarter-over-quarter growth in contract value

Portfolio Composition

  • DOJ component analysis reveals specialized relationships between certain contractors and specific DOJ Components
  • The heatmap visualization demonstrates how contractors have positioned themselves across different DOJ components

Performance Metrics

  • Contract duration statistics reveal differences in engagement length across contractors
  • Modification patterns indicate which contractors are more successful at expanding initial contract scope

Key Takeaways

Of the top 10 leading contractors within the U.S. federal government, Leidos leads contracting volume with $344.6 million in obligations. Booz Allen Hamilton shows high specialization, focusing 85.4% of its DOJ work with FBI. Guidehouse leads with the most frequent expansion of their contracts, with an average of 5.21 modfications. Leidos holds the longest average contract durations at 1,161 days.

Recommendations

  1. Identify High-Concentration Risk Areas: Target DOJ components showing excessive reliance on single contractors; implement supplier diversification strategies to reduce operational vulnerabilities.
  2. Redistribute Procurement Timing: Eliminate the pattern of concentrated Q4 spending surges that result in rushed, suboptimal contracts. Implement quarterly procurement targets to distribute actions evenly throughout the fiscal year.
  3. Strengthen Requirements Definition: Address the high volume of contract modifications by improving initial scoping documents. Better requirements definition will minimize costly modifications and reduce contractor leverage.
  4. Scrutinize Contractor Teaming Arrangements: Review existing teaming relationships for potential anti-competitive practices. Break up concentrated contractor teams to increase competition and reduce costs.
  5. Implement Insourcing Assessment: For routine services with predictable workloads, conduct cost-benefit analyses for bringing functions in-house. Target areas where contractor premiums no longer represent good value.
  6. Standardize Contract Vehicles: Replace contractor-specific agreements with standardized, competitive vehicles that allow for easier vendor substitution and increased negotiating leverage.

Contract Volume and Value

The distribution of DOJ contract obligations is heavily skewed towards the top 10 contractors, who capture a disproportionately large share of overall spending. This concentration suggests varying engagement models among contractors, as evidenced by the substantial differences in average contract sizes.

Leidos leads in total obligations ($344.6.1 million), accounting for the largest portion of DOJ spending (~16%). SAIC leads with the number of contracts (1,626). Booz Allen Hamilton has the largest average contract size ($1.6 million).

Temporal Patterns

The following reveals distinct patterns in DOJ contract spending, which highlights strategic contractor positioning and agency spending behaviors.

Quarterly spending patterns show significant concentration in Q4, particularly for Booz Allen Hamilton, indicating potential "use it or lose it" budget execution at fiscal year-end. Several other contractors demonstrate quarter-to-quarter volatility rather than steady growth, suggesting project-based rather than retainer-based engagement models. SAIC maintains consistent high-value engagement across multiple quarters, indicating stable, long-term contractual relationships.

Outsized Year-over-Year Growth

Year-over-year spending growth varies dramatically between contractors, with Booz Allen Hamilton (98.6%) and Guidehouse (91%) showing considerable expansion between FY23-24. General Dynamics experienced a notable decline (-21.5%) in DOJ contract obligations year-over-year.

Portfolio Composition

This analysis reveals how the top contractors have strategically positioned themselves within the Department of Justice (DOJ) to secure a consistent stream of awards and potentially limit competition.

Component Specialization

The heatmap of contractor activity by DOJ component demonstrates clear specialization patterns. Booz Allen Hamilton and CGI Federal have cultivated a dominant presence within FBI and OBD, respectively. This specialization creates a barrier to entry for new competitors, as these incumbents possess deep institutional knowledge and established trust.

Award Type Dominance

The heatmap of contractor activity by award type further illustrates strategic positioning. It reveals the dominance of certain contract types among the top contractors. This suggests a preference for specific procurement methods, potentially limiting the use of other contract vehicles that could foster broader competition or innovation. IBM, SAIC, and Accenture secure virtually all of their contracts through delivery orders, which indicates a strong reliance on this specific award type.

Encourage DOJ components to utilize a broader range of contract vehicles to avoid over-reliance on specific award types favored by incumbent contractors. Implement pilot programs that incentivize contractors to propose innovative solutions through less conventional award types (e.g., prize challenges, Other Transaction Authorities).

Performance Metrics

Contract duration statistics highlight variations in engagement length across different contractors, while modification patterns reveal which contractors are more adept at expanding the scope of their initial agreements.

Contract Durations

The visualization of average contract durations highlights contractors with potentially inefficient long-term engagements. Scrutinize these contracts, especially those with Leidos, for opportunities to implement performance-based milestones and earlier termination options.

Contract Modifications

The visualization of average contract modifications identifies contractors who frequently expand their initial agreements. Implement more rigorous requirements definition processes to reduce the need for modifications, focusing on Guidehouse, IBM, and Deloitte to control costs and improve project predictability.
